I. The Business Problem

ABD contains data for all the customers in the dataset that were already pursued (advertised) but ended up not buying a vacation package.

Business Problem: Should we retarget those customers?

Q1: In light of your experience as a business woman/man, argue why this is a sensible business question.

Ans. Most of the time a majority of first time visitors are not ready to purchase. So there is a need to encourage the visitors to return more often to the site. Retargeting is the best way to target the first time visitors. It helps to target existing prospects and reduces the effort in acquiring new ones. And this makes the overall marketing campaign cheaper and cost effective.

An experiment is run, where customers in the abandoned dataset are randomly placed in a treatment or in a control group (see column L in both files).Those marked as “test” are retargeted (treated), the others marked as control are part of the control group.

Q2: compute the summary statistics (mean, median, q5, q95, standard deviation) of the Test_variable: a dummy with a value of 1 if tested 0 if control in the ABD database.

#unique identifier

The data matching process in Abandoned (AB) and Reservation(RS) dataset:
-Assigning all missing values in both AB and RS dataset as NA.
-Match the customers in AB file and RS file based on Email address only as email-id’s are always uniquie.
-Match the customers in AB and RS file on Contact Phone only as this is given by the customer while calling in.
-Match the customers in AB and RS file based on combination of Last Name and Incoming phone.
-Match the customers in AB and RS file based on combination of First Name, Last Name and Zip code.
-Combine all the customer matches in a single list.
Remove duplicate customers based on each Keys - Email, First name, Last name, Contact phone, Incoming phone, Zip code.
-There are 192 matched customers and they are marked as ‘1’ in variable “MatchRS” in Abandoned Data set.

Q8: Are there problematic cases? i.e. data records not matchable? If so, provide a few examples and toss those cases out of the analysis.

I had to focus on the uniqueness of a field and then determine combinations to be used as a key. The contact phone number is provoded by the customer so that was used as a key. The email id is unique for the customer and is used as key. Many of the contact address, email, contact phone ,incoming phone and names had NA’s. So matches were made on each key or a combination and then aggregated.

#Email match
reservation_email_match <- match(Abandoned_Data_Seed_10$Email, Reservation_Data_Seed_09$Email, nomatch = 0, incomparables = NA)

#Contact Phone match
reservation_contact_phone_match <- match(Abandoned_Data_Seed_10$Contact_Phone, Reservation_Data_Seed_09$Contact_Phone, nomatch = 0, incomparables = NA)



#Incoming phone and Last name match
reservation_lastname_incoming_match <- ifelse(!is.na(Abandoned_Data_Seed_10$Last_Name) & !is.na(Abandoned_Data_Seed_10$Incoming_Phone),
match(paste0(Abandoned_Data_Seed_10$Last_Name,Abandoned_Data_Seed_10$Incoming_Phone), paste0(Reservation_Data_Seed_09$Last_Name,Reservation_Data_Seed_09$Incoming_Phone), nomatch = 0, incomparables = NA),0)


#Fisrt name last name and Zip code
reservation_Custname_zip_match <- ifelse(!is.na(Abandoned_Data_Seed_10$First_Name) & !is.na(Abandoned_Data_Seed_10$Last_Name) & !is.na(Abandoned_Data_Seed_10$Zipcode),match(paste0(Abandoned_Data_Seed_10$First_Name,Abandoned_Data_Seed_10$Last_Name,Abandoned_Data_Seed_10$Zipcode), paste0(Reservation_Data_Seed_09$First_Name,Reservation_Data_Seed_09$Last_Name,Reservation_Data_Seed_09$Zipcode), nomatch = 0, incomparables = NA),0)

Accuracy
## [1] 0.507109

The area under the ROC curve is 65%. The true positive rate or the sensitivity at 78% is good which measures the proportion of actual positives or actual conversion in our case that are correctly identified. The true negative rate is 50%. The False positive(=1029) is also high, so the false alarm is high and this may distort the prediction of conversion.

Q16: Lesson Learned. What would you have done differently in designing the experiment? Any other directions you could have taken with better data? Are there any prescriptive managerial implications out of this study? Please answer briefly.

In this experiment, there was a limitation in matching customers due to missing key information in the abandoned dataset. So we could barely match customers who were randomly placed in a treatment group and retargeted as (treat=1). Hence, if every customer is assigned a unique customer ID and if we had valid values for the various attributes of the customer,it would have been easy in matching and understanding the retargeting effects. With the very limited amount of data that could be matched, we could not draw inference from different States as to which State has the most effective conversion rate.

In the model we see that Days in between has a negative effect on the outcome of conversion and is significant. The larger the number of days between the actual call and the reservation call, the less will be the probability to actually make a reservation. The R2 has also significantly increasesd making this a very good model fit.

So the recommendation from the fit model is that retargeting does help in conversion. Customers should be retargetted before a certain time to achieve maximum probablity of conversion.
